    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4b5ee2ff_598de694",
        "filename": "client/crashpad_client_win_test.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-03-23T20:24:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Since we have a process handle by this point, a more direct way to answer this would be to make a ProcessInfo from it and check that its ParentProcessID() matches GetProcessId(parent). We’ve already got the code we need to do that, just #include \"util/win/process_info.h\".\n\nThat would mean putting GetProcessId(parent) here, so you’d want to change GetPotentialChildProcessesOf() to accept that instead of the handle that it takes now.\n\nAlternatively, you can take the “potential” out of the inner function, have it evaluate ProcessInfo::ParentProcessID(), and make it return a std::vector\u003cHANDLE\u003e instead of a std::vector\u003cDWORD\u003e. But then freeing all of the handles becomes a hassle, and I don’t know if std::vector\u003cScopedKernelHANDLE\u003e works.",
      "revId": "3c1accd21450eb4a0248d2f0ed5e5a36e5e205dc",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "13c1069e_a8585db5",
        "filename": "client/crashpad_client_win_test.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 1177549
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-03-24T15:25:39Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "No, all the processes here have |parent|\u0027s PID as parent PID.  The problem is that a PIDs are aggressively reused on Windows. You can therefore have a process that has a parent PID that belonged to a now-exited process, where that PID was reassigned to |parent|.\nTo resolve the ambiguity, you have to look at creation times, so a process that was created before |parent| was, can\u0027t be a child process of |parent|, even if its parent PID points to it.\nWhile there\u0027s at least one handle open to |parent|, the ambiguity doesn\u0027t go in the other direction as |parent| is in the process table and safely occupies the PID. As soon as the last handle to |parent| closes, it\u0027s reaped from the process table, you get that too...\n\nActually, you\u0027re right, the PPID has to be checked too, as the child process\u0027 PID may have been reused *sigh*.",
      "parentUuid": "4b5ee2ff_598de694",
      "revId": "3c1accd21450eb4a0248d2f0ed5e5a36e5e205dc",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cb86bf6e_ff073be7",
        "filename": "client/crashpad_client_win_test.cc",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-03-24T15:54:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e No, all the processes here have |parent|\u0027s PID as parent PID.  The problem is that a PIDs are aggressively reused on Windows. You can therefore have a process that has a parent PID that belonged to a now-exited process, where that PID was reassigned to |parent|.\n\nMy thinking was tainted by POSIX semantics, where when a process’ parent dies, its parent process ID becomes 1.",
      "parentUuid": "13c1069e_a8585db5",
      "revId": "3c1accd21450eb4a0248d2f0ed5e5a36e5e205dc",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
